[1] Guadeloupe, Martinique (French Antilles)
Date: Sun, 14 Aug 2005 17:02:07 -0400 (EDT)
From: Thomas Roesel <roesel@lycos.com>
Source: Invs.sante.fr, 12 Aug 2005 [translated by submitter, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2005/le_point_sur/dengue_120805/index.html>

Guadeloupe
---------
Since June 2005, the available dengue epidemiological surveillance data
reveal a steady increase in the number of cases reported each
week. Epidemic onset was identified as from the beginning of July, after
the daily epidemic threshold of suspected dengue cases had been passed for
2 consecutive weeks, as determined by the sentinel physician network.
In June, the most affected areas are those of southern Basse-Terre
(Basse-Terre, Saint-Claude, and Gourbeyre) as well as Saint-Martin
island. Between the 1 and 6 Aug 2005, a network of sentinel physicians
reported 158 suspected clinical cases and 142 cases that had been confirmed
by biological analysis. Geographical expansion of the epidemic is
ongoing. Cases of dengue have now been reported in areas of central
Basse-Terre, on Grande-Terre, and on Marie-Galante island.
Martinique
--------
The threshold for the seasonal recurrence of dengue has already receded in
an abnormally premature manner; the epidemic threshold, beginning since
mid-June, receded by mid-July 2005. Those areas most affected by this were
those centrally located (Fort de France, Lamentin, Saint-Joseph, and
Schoelcher), those south (Riviere Pilote, Marin, and Francois), and those
north (Trinite and Basse Pointe). Between the 1 Jun 2005 and 10 Aug 2005,
the sentinel physician network reported 242 suspected cases of dengue; of
those, 234 cases had been confirmed by biological analyses. Extrapolating
from the sentinel network data, it is estimated that 1200 persons had been
infected in Martinique since the beginning of the epidemic.
Management Measures
-----------
The administrative committees for the plan for surveillance notification
and management of dengue epidemics (Plan de surveillance, d'alerte et de
gestion des epidemies de dengue, or Psage-Dengue) has initiated, in
Guadeloupe and in Martinique, notification of the population by a radio and
audiovisual awareness campaign, as well as by targeted actions at the
community level. Mosquito eradication steps to combat _Aedes aegypti_ have
been reinforced, as well as the epidemiological surveillance system. The
principal hospitals of the 2 departments (Guadeloupe and Martinique) are
prepared for the eventual influx of ill persons.
Recommendations
-----------
To prevent infection, it is important to:
1) Protect oneself against mosquito bites (use of mosquito nets, wearing
long-sleeved shirts and pants, use of insect repellents and insecticides)
2) Avoid permitting mosquitoes to proliferate by regularly eliminating all
breeding grounds, which can be found inside and outside houses.
--
Thomas Roesel, MD, PhD, FACP
<roesel@lycos.com>
