[2] Philippines (Misamis Occidental)
Date: Mon, 15 Aug 2005 15:36:59 -0400 (EDT)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sun.Star,Philippines, 15 August 2005 [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/cag/2005/08/15/news/dengue.outbreak.also.hits.misamis.occidental.html>

Dengue outbreak also hits Misamis Occidental
---------------------------------------------------
Following the example of Cebu, a state of calamity was also declared in
Misamis Occidental in connection with the alarming outbreak of dengue fever
in the province.
This was contained in a resolution unanimously approved by provincial
legislators Friday.
Board Member Morpheus Agot, who spearheaded the measure, expressed
confidence the Provincial Government would be in a financially better
position to respond to the situation because its calamity fund is now made
available for disposition.
Dengue fever cases have been noted throughout the province's 17 localities.
From June 2005 until the present, there are 349 known cases, 9 of which
led to death. Those afflicted were mostly children.
However, the hotspots are in the cities of Tangub, Ozamiz and Oroquieta
where the most incidences occurred.
Of the 9 deaths, 8 are children and one teenager. 6 of the dead are from
Tangub City.
Governor Loreto Ocampos has also ordered the acquisition of an additional
platelet separator for the provincial hospital to hasten the process of
preparing for platelet transfusion for those patients who need it.
Agot said 3500 pesos [USD 65] will be provided as death aid for those
families who lost their children to dengue fever.
Meanwhile, Agot criticized Health Secretary Francisco Duque for "his
adamant stand not to declare a state of national calamity" in the face of
the mushrooming dengue cases in the country.
He said such a declaration would put greater government attention into the
problem, and hence, ensure its faster resolution.
[Byline: Ryan Rosauro]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Cebu, as reported in the earlier posting (see also: 20050727.2201), and
Misamis Occidental, in this report, have shown an unusual upsurge of dengue
cases, approaching the critical point of whether the health authorities
declare a state of calamity or not. The entire Philippines has encountered
a 40 percent increase in dengue cases so far this year compared to the same
period of 2004. Political involvement and public awareness are both
essential for preventing the seasonal epidemics from worsening. - Mod.RY]
******
[3] Vietnam
Date: Thu, 11 Aug 2005 05:49:07 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source:Xinhua, China, 10 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-08/11/content_3338962.htm>

Vietnam detected 5500 dengue fever patients in the southern Mekong Delta
over the past month, raising the total number so far this year to more than
15 500, including 17 fatalities [a tentative case fatality rate or CFR of
110 per 100 000].
Most of local sufferers are from the provinces of Soc Trang, Dong Thap, Hau
Giang, An Giang and Bac Lieu, whose weather is most favorable for the
development of mosquitoes -- the disease's transmitter, according to local
newspaper Saigon Liberation on Thursday.
Local health agencies forecast that the disease could break out in August
and September. They are encouraging residents to kill mosquitoes and their
larvae more actively.
Vietnam reported 73 300 cases of dengue fever infection, including 101
fatalities [a CFR of 138 per 100 000] last year [2004], up 108 percent and
74 percent against the previous year [2003], respectively.
